"Mahlstein I., Knutti R., Solomon S., Portmann R.W.","Early onset of significant local warming in low latitude countries",2011,"Environmental Research Letters","6","3", 034009,"","",,,10.1088/1748-9326/6/3/034009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053558242&partnerID=40&md5=4b94ece46b8cd8154a7b6395037c57f3","Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland; NOAA Earth System Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO 80305, United States","Mahlstein, I., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Knutti, R., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Solomon, S., NOAA Earth System Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; Portmann, R.W., NOAA Earth System Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO 80305, United States","The Earth is warming on average, and most of the global warming of the past half-century can very likely be attributed to human influence. But the climate in particular locations is much more variable, raising the question of where and when local changes could become perceptible enough to be obvious to people in the form of local warming that exceeds interannual variability; indeed only a few studies have addressed the significance of local signals relative to variability. It is well known that the largest total warming is expected to occur in high latitudes, but high latitudes are also subject to the largest variability, delaying the emergence of significant changes there. Here we show that due to the small temperature variability from one year to another, the earliest emergence of significant warming occurs in the summer season in low latitude countries (≈25°S-25°N). We also show that a local warming signal that exceeds past variability is emerging at present, or will likely emerge in the next two decades, in many tropical countries. Further, for most countries worldwide, a mean global warming of 1 °C is sufficient for a significant temperature change, which is less than the total warming projected for any economically plausible emission scenario. The most strongly affected countries emit small amounts of CO2 per capita and have therefore contributed little to the changes in climate that they are beginning to experience. © 2011 IOP Publishing Ltd.","local detection",,,,,,,"Baettig, M.B., Wild, M., Imboden, D.M., A climate change index: Where climate change may be most prominent in the 21st century (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, p. 17711; Barnett, T.P., Schlesinger, M.E., Detecting changes in global climate induced by greenhouse gases (1987) J. Geophys. Res., 92 (D12), pp. 14772-14780; Battisti, D.S., Naylor, R.L., Historical warnings of future food insecurity with unprecedented seasonal heat (2009) Science, 323, pp. 240-244; Beaumont, L.J., Pitman, A., Perkins, S., Zimmermann, N.E., Yoccoz, N.G., Thuiller, W., Impacts of climate change on the world's most exceptional ecoregions (2011) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci., 108, pp. 2306-2311; Collins, J.M., Temperature variability over Africa (2009) J. Clim., 22, pp. 5854-5869; Deutsch, C.A., Tewksbury, J.J., Huey, R.B., Sheldon, K.S., Ghalambor, C.K., Haak, D.C., Martin, P.R., Impacts of climate warming on terrestrial ectotherms across latitude (2008) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 105 (18), pp. 6668-6672. , http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/105/18/6668, DOI 10.1073/pnas.0709472105; Gillett, N.P., Stone, D.A., Stott, P.A., Nozawa, T., Karpechko, A.Y., Hegerl, G.C., Wehner, M.F., Jones, P.D., Attribution of polar warming to human influence (2008) Nature Geosci., 1, pp. 750-754; Gillett, N.P., Zwiers, F.W., Weaver, A.J., Stott, P.A., Detection of human influence on sea-level pressure (2003) Nature, 422 (6929), pp. 292-294. , DOI 10.1038/nature01487; Giorgi, F., Bi, X.Q., Time of emergence (TOE) of GHG-forced precipitation change hot-spots (2009) Geophys. 